{"cursor":"2387","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Geniac' was an educational toy billed as a \"computer\" designed and marketed by\nEdmund Berkeley from 1955 through the 1960s. The name stood for \"Genius Almost-\nautomatic Computer.\"\n\nBasically a rotary switch construction set, the Geniac contained six perforated\nhardboard wheels, into which brass jumpers could be inserted. It had no active\nelements at all; no relays, tubes, or transistors. All sequencing was performed\nmanually by the operator, sometimes following fairly complicated printed\ndirections (turn this wheel in this direction if this light lights, etc.)\n\nThe instruction book gave jumper positions and wiring diagrams for building a\nnumber of \"computers.\" Electric current from a dry cell was routed through the\nrotary switches to light one or more flashlight bulbs. The kit allowed for the\nrealization of fairly complicated Boolean equations, so the behavior of the\n\"computer\" could sometimes be interesting.\n\nA typical project was a primitive \"masculinity-femininity tester.\" The user was\ninstructed to answer ten questions related to gender, such as \"Which makes a\nbetter toy for a child: a) a doll, b) a toy truck.\" For each\n\"a\" answer, one wheel was turned one position clockwise; for each \"b\" answer,\nanother wheel was turned one position clockwise. The circuit wiring effectively\ncompared the two wheel positions, and lit up a \"more masculine\" or \"more\nfeminine\" bulb depending on which wheel had been turned further.\n\nWidely advertised in science and electronics magazines, the Geniac provided\nmany youths with their first hands-on introduction to computer concepts and\nBoolean logic.\n\nA similar product, called Brainiac was introduced later. \n","linknr":94,"url":"Geniac","recorded":1363577823,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Geniac&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Geniac&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/Educational_toy","/wiki/Computer","/wiki/Edmund_Berkeley","/wiki/Rotary_switch","/wiki/Relay","/wiki/Transistor","/wiki/Jumper_(computing)","/wiki/Electric_current","/wiki/Dry_cell","/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(logic)","/w/index.php?title=Geniac&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Digi-Comp_I","/wiki/Digi-Comp_II","/w/index.php?title=Geniac&action=edit&section=2","http://www.oldcomputermuseum.com/geniac.html","http://www.oldcomputermuseum.com/brainiac_k30.html","http://www.computercollector.com/archive/geniac/","/wiki/File:Rubik%27s_cube_scrambled.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Rubik%27s_cube_scrambled.svg/30px-Rubik%27s_cube_scrambled.svg.png","/wiki/Toy","/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Geniac&action=edit","/wiki/Template:Toy-stub","/wiki/Template_talk:Toy-stub","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Toy-stub&action=edit","http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Geniac&oldid=543220709","/wiki/Help:Categories","/wiki/Category:Mechanical_computers","/wiki/Category:Educational_toys","/wiki/Category:1955_introductions","/wiki/Category:Toy_stubs","/w/index.php?title=Special:UserLogin&returnto=Geniac&type=signup","/w/index.php?title=Special:UserLogin&returnto=Geniac","/wiki/Geniac","/